{"add":{"doc":{"id":"2edb07e74b667410c2243b0451a2db0bed4b0cd21d87af4b4dacfb087c578dd1","url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d2/Roger_Fenton%27s_waggon.jpg/220px-Roger_Fenton%27s_waggon.jpg","previous":["In 1851 Frederick Scott Archer invented the collodion process.[citation needed] Photographer and children's author Lewis Carroll used this process. (Carroll refers to the process as \"Tablotype\" [sic] in the story \"A Photographer's Day Out\")[23]"],"after":["Herbert Bowyer Berkeley experimented with his own version of collodion emulsions after Samman introduced the idea of adding dithionite to the pyrogallol developer.[citation needed] Berkeley discovered that with his own addition of sulfite, to absorb the sulfur dioxide given off by the chemical dithionite in the developer, that dithionite was not required in the developing process. In 1881 he published his discovery. Berkeley's formula contained pyrogallol, sulfite and citric acid. Ammonia was added just before use to make the formula alkaline. The new formula was sold by the Platinotype Company in London as Sulpho-Pyrogallol Developer.[24]"]}}}